I originally approached the problem wrong. Rather than looking at it from the perspective of simply solving for each subproblem and bringing these solutions together, I thought the program would need to be "smart" about HOW it went about the problems. Rather than checking every option (with the knowledge of the previous ones), I tried to make it almost greedy. I figured that if, for example, I had 13 digits, the only way to get the highest total would be to have 8 one digit numbers and one four digit number, and that the four digit number could be chosen by finding the highest single digit, going to the second and third and so on for ties. Unfortunately, this isn't always true, 0's mess it up and it doesn't make sence with more digits, but I didn't see this yet. I wrote the code to do it this way, wondering why it was so easy, and only when I tested it did I realize the flaws. I then spent hours looking at the notes, trying things on paper, and just generally letting the problem bounce around in my brain to figure out what I actually needed to do. This forced me to understand the concept of dynamic programming much better. The concept that did turn out to be correct came into my head a few times, but I thought it would still take WAY too much time, until finally I decided to try to think through the time complexity of it and realized it would be much better than I thought, as I had failed to realize just how much time would be saved by the memoizing. I then typed out the code to take the input, and the basic recursive case of solving the minimum number of digits, and then increasing until reaching the maximum. I then made my base case and began testing. Of course there were many bugs, one of them simply being int size overflow issues, but as I worked through them, I was very excited to get the correct result from the test I had been using. I then put in the next test, which was much larger and it didn't work. After a while, I realized I recognized the issue I was having, but couldn't remember what the problem or solution were, so I spent hours tracing my code, thinking the reason the last number was always wrong was related to an issue with how I was adding my values, only to finally realize that the unsigned int wasn't long enough. Once I switched to long unsigned int, I was able to make it work.
